Part I:¶

  1. Perform k-means clustering on different data sets using different k (e.g., 2-6)
In [3]:
from sklearn import cluster
compound = data1.drop(['Class'],axis=1)
k_means = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=2, max_iter=50, random_state=1)
k_means.fit(compound)
labels = pd.DataFrame(k_means.labels_,columns =['Cluster ID'])
result = pd.concat((compound, labels), axis=1)
  1. Visualize the clustering results using scatter plots for different k
In [4]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

result.plot.scatter(x='col1', y='col2')
plt.title('Compound Dataset')
Out[4]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Compound Dataset')
  1. Calculate the SSE and plot sum-of-squared errors (SSE) versus k
In [5]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

numClusters = [2,3,4,5,6]
SSE = []
for k in numClusters:
    k_means = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    k_means.fit(compound)
    SSE.append(k_means.inertia_)

plt.plot(numClusters, SSE)
plt.title('Plot of Sum-of-squared errors - Compound')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('SSE')
Out[5]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'SSE')
  1. Discuss the results of part (2) and (3)

For part (2) I noticed the visually obvious clusters For part (3) I noticed the value of the best K didn't seem obvious.

Part II:¶

  1. Perform DBSCAN clustering on different data sets using different Eps and MinPt
  2. Draw the distance to k nearest point versus k (for different k)
    • Try to find the estimation of Eps and MinPt (see DBSCAN: Determining EPS and MinPts slide)
In [6]:
from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN
import numpy as np

db = DBSCAN(eps=0.5, min_samples=2).fit(data1)
labels = pd.DataFrame(db.labels_,columns=['Cluster ID'])
result = pd.concat((data1,labels), axis=1)
result.plot.scatter(x='col1', y='col2',c='Cluster ID', colormap='jet')
Out[6]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='col1', ylabel='col2'>
In [7]:

In [8]:
from sklearn.neighbors import NearestNeighbors
import numpy as np
from scipy.spatial import distance

neighbors = NearestNeighbors(n_neighbors = 4)
neighbors_fit = neighbors.fit(compound)
distances, indices = neighbors_fit.kneighbors(compound)

distances = np.sort(distances, axis=0)
distances = distances[:,1]
plt.plot(distances)
plt.ylabel('4-NN Distance')
plt.xlabel('Points Sorted by Distance')
plt.title('Compound Dataset')
Out[8]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Compound Dataset')

Part III:¶

  1. Compare the results of part I and II and discuss the advantages and limitations

Part I didn't have color distinguished pictorial depiction of the points where as Part II did have multiple vartiations of that distinguished pictorial depiction. Ultimately yeilding better clusters.

In this section, the non-globals was a limitation
